## ASP.NET → ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Migration

### Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Response.End()`** — doesn't exist. It threw `ThreadAbortException` internally; .NET Core removed `Thread.Abort` entirely.
2. **`Response.Redirect(url, endResponse: true)`** — the `endResponse` parameter is gone. Redirects no longer abort the thread.
3. **`ThreadAbortException`** — never thrown in .NET Core. Catching it is dead code.
4. **WebForms event handlers** (`btnExport_Click`) — don't exist in MVC/Core. Use action methods returning `IActionResult`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Return a FileResult — no need to manually clear/write/end the response
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    // POST /Report/Redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No ThreadAbortException catch — it cannot be thrown in .NET Core
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

### Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Code after redirect still runs** | In Framework, `Response.Redirect(url, true)` aborted execution. In Core, code after `return Redirect()` in the same method won't run (it's a return), but in middleware/filters it will. Always `return` immediately. |
| **`Response.Write` in filters** | If you used `Response.Write` + `Response.End` in action filters, replace with writing to `Response.Body` and setting `context.Result` to short-circuit. |
| **`HttpContext.Current`** | Gone. Use constructor injection of `IHttpContextAccessor` if needed outside controllers. |
| **`Thread.Abort`** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET Core. Any library relying on it will break. |
| **Null-ref on `User.Identity`** | Can be `null` in Core if no auth middleware is configured — use null-conditional (`?.`). |

### If You Must Stream a Response Manually

```csharp
[HttpGet]
public async Task ExportStream()
{
    Response.ContentType = "text/csv";
    Response.Headers.ContentDisposition = "attachment; filename=report.csv";

    await Response.WriteAsync(GenerateReport());
    // No Response.End() — just let the method complete.
    // The framework closes the response automatically.
}
```

**Rule of thumb:** Replace every `Response.End()` / `Response.Redirect(..., true)` with an `IActionResult` return. The action pipeline handles the rest.
